content: Waste of time. Use Hinge. Here's why: 1) This app is a ghost town. Nobody really uses the app, because nobody uses the app, because nobody uses it, etc. Matches very rarely lead to meaningful conversations -- nothing ever goes anywhere. I have over 200 matches on Hinge & overall the experience is way better. People won't respond to you because they've gotten tired of the app, and are looking elsewhere. By the time they look back at the app, it's been a week. Maybe they'll message you, but by the time you see their message, it's been another week. Things fizzle out. The problem is an engagement death spiral. You get very few "prospects" per day. The matchmaking algorithm is very bad at showing you people that are mutually compatible. Why? Probably the main reason is that because there are so few prospects, there is very little data for the algorithm to show you good matches. These kinds of algorithms need a lot of data to be accurate. Because the matches are bad, people don't really use the app because they're disappointed, so the algorithm has even less data to give you good matches, and so on. The idea of a having a few "prospects" a day sounds great, but in execution is a failure. The format is incredibly dry, which makes it hard to start a conversation. All of the side events, and other feature are also complete failures not even worth discussing. 2) This app is not exclusive. There's literally no difference between the people I see in this app and others. I often see the same profile in both. This is not an app for "elite singles". Unless you consider primary school teachers and dancers as "elite" -- if that's something important to you. "Elite dating" does exist, but it costs $5000-$20,000 and comes from matchmakers, who are also likely to be scammers. The League is selling you something it cannot provide. Think about it. How can an app be freemium, and also exclusive? When you make something exclusive, that means a small percentage of people are using it. And if it's freemium, that means an even smaller number of people paying money. So how can this app be freemium, and elite, and also not go bankrupt? Well here's how: 3) Its paid version is a scam. I wasn't dumb enough to pay for this. There are literally hundreds of other reviews that will explain how this is a waste of money, so I will leave it to others. Don't pay to get off the wait list. Just sign up and after a few weeks, they'll let you in. If they didn't do this, the could never be profitable. A small percentage of people are impatient, and will pay believing that this app is exclusive. It may take them a few months to realize that they're wasting their money, and I'm pretty sure that's the entire business model of the company. Is there any other way in which this app could fail? There is literally no reason to download this app. Download Hinged and The League and use both. I will pay you $1000 if you get a date on The League before you get a date on Hinged.
replyContent: Hi Robert, Thank you for taking the time out of your day to write a review about our App. We truly appreciate all reviews. We feel you should email support@theleague.com to get help with your Prospects and Matching.

content: If you sign up, chances are you'll be placed in a queue, for me it said there were over 10,000 people in line in front of me. I could pay to expedite the process, or I could wait. After about a week, the number had dropped a little bit, and despite there being over 10,000 people in line in front of me, I was let in. I believe this is done simply to get people to pay, so they try to make it seem like there are a lot of people on the app and tons more waiting to get in. However, once you get in, virtually every single aspect of the app is monetized (and the prices are ridiculous). Hinge, bumble, and tinder handle monetization way better. They give you a few matches every day, not because as they claim, for quality matches, but because there are not many people who use the app. This is why after about a week or so, the app was reverting to showing me people in neighboring cities over an hour away or two away. The company is trying to market themselves as this high end dating app with an exclusive user base featuring high quality matches by reviewing and approving all the people they let in, but I find it's simply a shameless money grab. Stick to Hinge, bumble, or tinder.

content:
I'm not Ivy League or an MBA but I was in just under three weeks after 
signing up in the NYC area. Patience is a virtue, I guess.

This app is not about instant gratification unlike so many other dating 
apps. It's not about finding a FWB or hook up. It's also not for everyone. 
So I'm really not surprised half the people love it and half hate it. This 
app is for quality professional singles who are serious about find real 
connections. If that description fits you then you will love this app. 
After being on the waiting for a couple weeks I started to see three 
profiles a day to like or not. Yes only three. However the quality of those 
three was incredible. Because profiles are often linked to LinkedIn the 
information you know about them tells you a lot about them and vice versa. 
There are ZERO fake accounts. ZERO spam. A concierge gives you tips on how 
to improve your profile. Anyway, after maybe a month I got my first match. 
It's been, I think two months I've had only four matches. HOWEVER! I'm not 
looking for four connections. Only one... And all four are wonderful, 
professional, quality people of substance that any guy should be proud to 
call their friends... Much less their GF or wives. So I'm actually not 
looking for any more matches until I see where things go with someone I've 
met here. You must be patient. You must be a professional or you will feel 
out of your league - that's probably the point. But if you're both of those 
things this is the dating app for you!!

This app is a waste of time outs you on a giant Waite list than pulls

content:
This app is supposed to be better because you have to be an active user to 
stay on it, and they reward your activity- logging in regularly, being the 
first to initiate communication, response time, etc.- with boosting your 
profile and giving you more possible matches. Yet there are still users who 
will get a match and neither initiate conversation nor respond. Of course, 
this is not really something the app can be responsible for, but it is 
still a disappointment. One major disappointment the app creators are 
responsible for, is how easy it is to accidentally x out a match, and how 
much they charge you to undo it. There is no "are you sure" popup when you 
x a match, making the app feel a lot more like tinder than a higher-quality 
matchmaking app. That image is further enhanced when you figure out that 
the app's currency - tickets- cannot be earned in any way, cannot be 
purchased in single quantities, and are not available at a reasonable price 
(it's $25 for FIVE). In my opinion, as a serious user of the app who 
doesn't have a disposable income to waste on something as impossible to 
guarantee as a dating app, this issue alone- the ease of accidentally 
skipping a match combined with the unrealistic cost of undoing such a 
mistake- is a major flaw and I sincerely hope they fix it.
replyContent: Hi Alicia, thanks for the feedback! As your concierge mentioned, you can actually earn League Tickets by making Endorsements if you'd rather not purchase a bundle. Also, feel free to reach out to your concierge for great opening lines to help spur along conversation.We penalize Flakes/Ghosts! As for X vs Heart, appreciate the suggestion on spacing!

content: • Obviously, potential dates on The League come vetted. They’re more professionally-minded than your average person. This infuriated me, since it felt like extortion.  I was told a day or two later by the Concierge that deleting my existing matches was a glitch, but I was being asked to pay to get new potential matches because I had been flagged as a "flaky" user (although that was being cancelled to make up for the first goof.) I mentioned that I thought this was odd, because I made a point never to ghost.  Today I received an email telling me that they had beta-tested an anti-ghosting feature, and I had wrongly been flagged as a "flaky" user. And I was compensated with League tickets.  There is plenty to complain about with the League as with all dating apps. I've still been ghosted a lot, even here. The thing that gives me hope is that the League seems to recognize problems that other apps are ignoring and is actually trying to fix them, even if the execution is imperfect.

content: For a successful dating app, you need competent leadership in 3 areas: 1. Business; 2. Social/dating expertise 3. Tech expertise. The developers here only have 1 out of the 3. They seem to have the tech part down... But they don't have a clue about business, the needs and concerns of consumers, consumer behavior or how to launch a venture. They are also clueless about dating culture and how humans interact. Whether or not the tech piece is solid enough is even questionable at this point. This is why it is faultering. Cherrypicking which cities are even allowed to participate was a huge mistake. I was shocked to learn (when I discovered the app about a year ago) that it waa only in a small handful of cities. I am frustrated to no end with low quality dating sites with no vetting...and would be happy to pay $100...$150 and an annual fee of $100 (give or take a few bucks) thereafter. And i'm sure there are thousands more like me.... but they won't let us in...because we aren't on the list of their chosen cities. Every major metro area should be included by this point. The influx of revenue would allow a sufficient staff for vetting. Every metro could have one staff member...and a volunteer vetting team...volunteers could be offered free memberships or gift cards. A notary or group of notaries in every large metro could be used to verify information. Applicants could also scan information and email it to the central office for additional verification. This would give applicants something to do to speed up the process....it puts the work in their hands...and they would have the motivation or drive to do it because they want in (saving $ on labor costs). The leadership of this project put too much focus on the LinkedIn/FB model and didn't have the vision to offer alternative pathways for joining. Those are 3 big failures (1. limiting cities & cherrypicking...which choked off revenue from applicants happy to pay larger than normal fees...this also choked off the dating pool early...when early on...you need a large, more active & enthusiastic pool of people. 2. Not utilizing members & applicants to do much of the work themselves and using notaries, saving on the cost of labor. A hybrid model involving consumers & a system of employees is called a sweat equity approach. I am more than willing to send in my ID and have my employment & ID, verified by a local notary and to do my own criminal record check or assist this company in the process of doing one. This is what you need for a startup such as this one- a sweat equity approach. 3. Relying too heavily -to the point of tunnel vision- on a shortsighted model involving LinkedIn & FB. When you have your business too closely reliant on other apps...you leave it vulnerable. It's survival would be dependant on those other apps. Those apps could change their privacy policies, TOS, could be sold to an unsavory entity, or could close for a number of reasons at any time without warning. The platform should have the ability to stand on its own. There are tons of other problems with the project as well. The leadership needs to pause & rethink their approach...change the structure & vetting procedures and start over with a new more comprehensive launch.  None of the waiting list nonsense. It should take no more than 30 days to get approved. If the leadership is too stubborn and refuses to change its approach...the project will fail. It likely needs new developers & new faces in their business mgt and R&D senior leadership teams.
replyContent: Hi Edward, thank you for your very well thought out feedback. As we're only allowed 350 characters to respond we can't touch on each point in depth. We can say that there's a very specific and calculated reason we focused on certain cities first; we actually do utilize our members/applicants but in a diff't way and LI/FB integration is only a step.
